## Type-Safe Milestone Enums

### Don't Accept Arbitrary Strings

```typescript
// ❌ BAD - accepts any string
export async function POST(req: Request) {
  const { milestone } = await req.json();
  await recordMilestone(milestone); // Could be anything
}

// ✅ GOOD - validates against known set
const VALID_MILESTONES = new Set(['firstAutomatedTrade', 'activationCompleted']);

export async function POST(req: Request) {
  const { milestone } = await req.json();
  
  if (typeof milestone !== 'string' || !VALID_MILESTONES.has(milestone)) {
    return NextResponse.json({ error: 'Invalid milestone' }, { status: 400 });
  }
  
  // Now safe to use
  await recordMilestone(milestone);
}
```

**Why:**
- Prevents typos in API calls (`firstTrade` vs `firstAutomatedTrade`)
- Self-documenting (set shows all valid values)
- Type-safe (TypeScript knows milestone is one of the valid strings)

